author: Acid Wizard
text: How much of a difference does it make whether the radiator on the AIO is mounted on the front (like they did) or the top (like I've always heard is the better way to do it)?

author: Acid Wizard
text: @Fuzzy Tech Thanks for the explanation. I have my radiator on top and just assumed that was the best way to do it since hot air will naturally rise through the top and away from the radiator even without fans. Radiator on top mean fresh cool air is being pulled in unabated from the front and then expelled out the top after the GPU and or CPU heat it. What do you think about having a cpu cooler with a top radiator and one of the gpu's with a cooler attached with the radiator on the front?

author: Fuzzy Tech
text: Not a huge difference but if you put it on the front where the air is normally drawn in then you would be pulling fresh, cooler outside air directly through the radiator where as on top, the warmer PC air is being pushed through the radiator. Keep in mind though there usually isn't a huge difference in temp, maybe two or three degrees in most cases. It mostly comes down to how you want to mount it as long as the pump isn't the highest part of the loop (don't want the air bubbles to collect around the pump).

author: Shane
text:
Well, I never build a top-of-the-line PC, so I'll take AMD for the AM5 upgradability.

Had a B550 with a 3600, then, when the 5800X dropped to $200, I got that, and now I'm good for another 2 years. Then, I'll get a mid-range AM5, and 2-3 years later, get the high-end last-gen AM5 CPU, which will carry me another 3 years from purchase. 

With Intel, I'm pretty much stuck with replacing the MOBO every time I upgrade, because I don't upgrade every year. 

Considering that the initial  build price is almost identical, and the performance as well... Why the hell choose Intel? I'll take a 2% initial performance hit for a $200 saved in the MOBO, and easier upgrade (just update bios and drop a CPU in vs build almost the entire system all over again).

author: Craig Stillwell
text: #LinusTechTips Not including multiple units of the CPUs you are testing IS SCIENTIFICALLY INCORRECT. I see this is all tech videos, which I explained to Steve at #GamersNexus. You cannot conclude that CPU 1 (e.g., AMD) is 10% faster than CPU 2 (e.g., Intel) without testing many different units of the identical model. You absolutely need replication to conclude one is faster than the other because of variation among CPUs of the same model. This is where the term "silicon lottery" comes into play. Overclockers know this, which is why no two same CPUs will overclock the same. There should be error bars on all graphs with performance comparisons so we know what the margin of error is. You do great work, so I thought this might be an interesting subject for a video since no one is doing this.

author: Craig Stillwell
text: I wanted to point out something that I see quite a bit in many videos on YouTube. I am not meaning to be too critical here, but comparing a cpu or gpu vs. another even in machines with identical specifications is not scientifically correct. Why? Because this requires replication, a fundamental of any science experiment. For example, the minimum comparison would ideally have 4 computers/test machines (more is better, but cost prohibitive) with identical specs, with two having the same cpu/gpu being tested vs. two that have the have the same cpu/gpu reference. Why? Because we know that individual cpus/gpus vary in their performance. I'm a senior data scientist,  which is why I am pointing this out. It would be awesome to do this type of test because I have never seen it done on YouTube. I hope this is helpful! Great work as always Linus!

author: Cris n Mary Fam
text:
It actually depends on the breaker, and the wiring that is between. That basic answer was incorrect at best, and very misleading. 
5-amp 120-volt circuit: 15 amps x 120 volts = 1,800 watts
20-amp 120-volt circuit: 20 amps x 120-volts = 2,400 watts
25-amp 120-volt circuit: 25 amps x 120 volts = 3,000 watts
20-amp 240-volt circuit: 20 amps x 240 volts = 4,800 watts
25-amp 240-volt circuit: 25 amps x 240 volts = 6,000 watts
30-amp 240-volt circuit: 30 amps x 240 volts = 7,200 watts
Assuming the wiring is up to code.

author: Patriot 03
text:
The performance difference at 4k disproves the myth you're spreading.. I'm so tired of hearing it over and over...

The performance difference is AWLASY THERE, it's just that as ms latency on the GPU becomes larger the apparent FPS difference also drops because measuring performance by FPS is an imperfect metric, the ms latency difference will always be present and the faster CPU will always result in a faster gaming experience. - That's before we even talking about games that actually have logic.... Anything with lots of AI for example, the real games we play not empty first person shooters with minimal actual game logic being processed on the CPU.

author: Network Engineer
text: I used to be an AMD fanboy. My first PC I built was AMD. For over 20 years I was all AMD until their FX Bulldozer line-up. Went through three FX-8350 CPUs and got tired of RMA'ing for a new CPU, so I decided to go Intel on my next build. I went from a disappointing AMD FX Bulldozer line-up to an Intel i9-9900K and never looked back. Until Intel gives me a real reason to move away from their products back to AMD, I'll stick with Intel. None of my Intel builds have ever let me down, and that was starting with their Core 2 Quad Q6600. That CPU outlasted the motherboard and power supply. I'm not saying I'm an Intel fanboy, but I'm still bitter about my break-up with AMD. It's like an ex that you want to go back to, but the memory of the pain keeps you from going back.

author: ShadowLordxsx
text: I found out something crazy about AMD cpus  a few weeks ago.....Back about 20 years ago I had a P3 with rambus memory and me and about 10 of us would get together at a friends and have lan parties. As games were requiring better hardware, I upgraded and went with a AMD cpu... All those games I had been playing went crazy, and i just thought it was the older game engines could not keep up with the new hardware.  A few weeks ago me and one of the people I used lan party with were talking and as I still had the original game from back then on my back up drive, i copied it over and fired it up....To say my jaw hit the floor is an under statement, as it played perfectly fine on this new computer. I just upgraded to this system earlier this year and the primary difference is that I bought an intel cpu that people were raving about as the best budget cpu at the time (i5-11400f) and I also have a rx6700xt vc.  Not even the person I was talking with can play it with the same version of windows as me (10 pro) no one else can play it as they all have AMD cpus. The last time I tried it was when I upgraded from a geforce 750ti to a rx570 on my old fx-8350 system and it still went nuts. I am speaking about a few games from back then that play fine now, but the game we played on a lan is the original unreal tournament

I honestly highly doubt the 5090 will come out within that 2 or 3 year time frame in 2024 or 2025. Cuz then That would assume it would take the same power draw as a 4090 (being 450 watts like the 3090) but the thing would be 30-50% more powerful than the 4090.
Nvidia was able to give the 4090 more shading cores, L2 cache, ray tracing cores, and tensor cores…. But it was only able to take that “supposedly” little power with that big of specs, because it’s 4nm compared to the 30 series being 8nm. I dunno if a different companies manufacturing process is different, and has different power draws…. But who knows.
I’d say the 5090 should be a 450/500 watt card, based on the full AD102 (but 2nm maybe), with more so a architecture refresh to give it more power. Because the architecture does determine how well the power of the gpu is, along with drivers.
We also have yet to see AMDs 7000 series, and if they deliver that “twice the performance” promise, but only having slight adjustments to the core/RT core count on the top end card. author: Patriot 03
text:
I swear the entire PC enthusiast community doesn't understand "CPU/GPU bottlenecks" - The 2 work in tandem all the time, even when the GPU is maxed out improved latency by way of a faster CPU WILL result in higher performance.

The ms latency difference will be a constant but FPS is an imperfect way of measuring performance because a 1 ms difference when you were already running 500 FPS will result in a massive FPS difference, usually when we're running 4K and maxing a GPU out the latency is so high from that demanding workload that the starting latency is much higher meaning your FPS is lower, in that scenario the difference of 1 ms in terms of FPS becomes much smaller but it's always there.

Tech channels really need to set the misnomer right and this video at least did it indirectly as you saw a moderate performance delta at 4k maxing both GPUs.

PS: Think about it in terms of percentage, if you were already running at 4ms per frame a difference of 2ms would literally DOUBLE your FPS, but if you're running 42ms, going down to 40ms isn't going to represent a massive percentage to framerate - but 2ms is always 2ms and being 2ms faster is always a win. IMO testing games at unrealistic framerates to exaggerate the percent performance difference is dishonest and not relevant to anyone. They do it to show more impressive graphs. What I really want to see is CPU demanding games like RTS and Open World RPGs not a shooter with almost no logic for the CPU to handle running at 720p 1000 FPS.

author: William Weathersby
text:
Couple of problems: 1) I would have waited to do this "test" when Gen 5 NVME was readily available. This test "gimps" the X670E by using Gen 4 drives when the 7950 supports Gen 5 NVME. 2) You are not using a 7900XTX which is CHEAPER, supports Gen 5 and doesn't have the bullshit power connector issue. The 4090 doesn't support Gen 5. The 7900XTX does :)
I would wait til you can pair a 7950 with a 7900XTX using Gen 5 NVME drives vs Intel 13900 and a 4090(Gen 4) Gen 4 NVME drives. Also factor in that the Z790 CANNOT support a GPU at x16 PCIE 5.0 AND do 1 to 2 NVME drives at full PCIE x8. The X670E can :)

author: Damien
text: cable mod are making one. But the main thing gamers nexus found in his video after lots of testing was the only mode of failure was from improper insertion. But the connector can appear inserted and not be and with a tight angle slowly pull out of the conntector. It seems a design flaw that the sense pins are so long and allow the connector to still drive power when its pulled way out of the card.

author: Rusty Shackleford
text:
probably difficult to do at that angle and pin density, without making it very large. You also have different points for failure such as the inner corner where there are two 'parallel' 90'd pins nested together with insulation between. Thats a strain point where the plastic (generally also performing insulation duties as a direct support) could be strained due to tugging and cause potential shorts.

Also, if the connector is too bulky, its could basically results in still being unable to close the case without strain.

Engineers have already started designing one (I believe cable-mod for sure), its just that ideas are worthless without execution, and that safety testing is super rigorous, especially after a widespread fire investigation on the original part.

author: Charles Hines
text: I don't mind LGA processors but I know if I ever install one be very careful NOT to damage that socket!  You don't even want your clothing to come in contact with it and get snagged on the delicate pins.  For that reason I would wear short sleeve shirt for it even in winter (just for the time it takes to get the chip safely in the socket).  I would also follow the CPU instructions to the letter for the LGAs.  It is not like the old ZIF sockets that you just open the socket and if the arrows are lined up it will just fall into place.  The ZIF sockets if the installation is done properly takes NO pressure on the chip.  In fact if you have to push on it you have the wrong chip or bent pins.  You might have also not lined it up correctly but if it does not go in under its own weight DO NOT try to force it or push it.  Then you will very likely damage either the socket or the CPU pins or both.  I know pins can be straightened but that would be really difficult and I would just prefer to avoid getting into that situation.  They are so close together on the AM4 chips you might find it challenging not to accidentally damage more pins straightening that one bent one.  Also keep in mind we don't know which pins we need so don't just break the offending pin off.  It may be one of the more critical ones.

author: Antares 8001

author: Antares 8001
text:
Both chips are gonna be perfectly fine for your needs unless you're at 1080p in which case just about everything is gonna bottleneck a 3090 ti, so if that's the case I'd recommend upgrading to a higher resolution or downsampling.
 All else being equal I'd probably go with the 7600x it's marginally faster in gaming and the AM5 platform will be compatible with future AMD CPUs giving you a long term upgrade path. Although from what I've seen AM5 motherboards are still considerably more expensive.

author: Llohr
text:
Another point in AMD's favor at this moment in time:

This is the first gen in a new socket.

That motherboard will likely have several generations of CPUs that it's compatible with before AMD starts using a different socket.

author: John D.
text:
Going with AMD saves money later. No motherboard upgrade and also no DDR5 upgrade(compared to an Intel system with DDR4). 

Try to calculate the total cost of buying a new system today and upgrading it once in 2-3 years and you will see that AM5 is cheaper.
Go further in time, calculate the costs for a CPU upgrade in 2-3 and 5-6 years and the costs are way lower with the AM5 option than going with the Intel platform.

author: James
text: I mean power draw, thermals, price, and future upgradability (track records) are all real things to consider. Intel will likely be making a new platform for the 14000 series while AMD just kicked off AM5. I'm not forgetting what happened with threadripper, but they literally killed the product line. So while the platform didn't last, there aren't new cpus either. Also AMD is running cooler, drawing (somewhat) less power, and the price is close. It's still a no brainer for AMD even if AMD is more expensive. You can literally calculate by hand how much the added power draw will cost you per year.  Also, if you live somewhere hot, the additional heat means more AC needed.

author: Christian
text:
Either of those setups is awesome - with the one exception.
Intel 13th gen currently outperforms nearly everything as far as memory speeds are concerned. A kit of Hynix M-die or A-die, and you're easily talking daily drivable memory speeds in the 7000-8000 MT range, at good timings (eg. C30-C34). Ryzen 7000 series doesn't come close (yet) as far as memory speeds are concerned; likely courtesy of Intel's 2nd gen DDR5 IMC.

author: Dethrok
text:
The main difference for me is futureproofing, which would've been cool to be covered in this conclusion as well.
AM5 is a new socket and AMD generally supports their sockets longer than Intel. LGA1700 on the other hand has already been on the market for over a year and if past trends are to be believed, this socket will be forgotten with 15th Gen Intel CPUs.

author: Kevin Vance
text: I'm an unapologetic AMD guy. Been using their CPUs since the K6-2 days. I have owned Intel, a Celeron 300a OC400, and an i5-2500k but that i5 was the most unstable system I ever owned. It would shut down randomly like someone flipped the power switch on the power strip. It would randomly reboot. Traced it down to a bad motherboard, but by then I was already buying parts to build an AMD FX-8120....yeah, I know it wasn't a great CPU. But it was stable. I am happy with my recent upgrade to a Ryzen 5 5600X, from my old Ryzen 5 2600 system though. Zen 3 is awesome.

Power efficiency is leaning towards a configuration option with how tuning tools are evolving.

author: David Baldock
text:
I've been considering building a new system, using an AMD Ryzen 9 7950X, or an Intel i9-13900K - but these CPUs have limited PCIe lanes to slots on the motherboards.
The 7950X has 28 PCIe 5.0 lanes (24 go to Slots, and 4 go to the Chipset), and the i9-13900K has 20 PCIe 5.0 lanes, and 4 PCIe 4.0 lanes.
That means neither one will support two PCIe x16 slots, in case you want to use one video card for the host OS, and pass a video card through to a VM.
I guess a Threadripper Pro 5955WX (at 2x the cost of the other two CPUs), with 128 PCIe 4.0 lanes, is currently the way to assemble a system with a bunch of x16 slots.

author: D827 Kelly
text:
The fact they are so close to each other is the best thing for the consumer really. 

Intel pros: more threads,  normally cheaper outside of sales, ddr4 still a option for other users 
Intel cons: 13900k is as good as you will get (apart from the probably ludicrous priced 13900ks coming next year.  14th gen is a new socket next year (probably ddr5 only too) and such things should be considered,  especially if you have the budget to get new cpus later 
Amd pros: more performance cores, more upgrade options with x3d on the horizon (which is probably going to blast the 13900k next year for gaming), better long term socket support 
Amd cons: initial price outside of sales, ddr5 only,  first gen teething trouble potentially. 

Overall I think with the two systems as shown I'd go amd as you don't need to buy any 10gb nic , which if you don't already have one eats whatever difference in cost exists anyway. Having the option to go 7950x3d (if it occurs of course,  might only go to 7800x3d) is a nice thing to have and being able to get zen5 and zen 6 chips and maybe even zen7 if it launches in 2025 is no bad thing imo either, especially as the extra am5 headroom allows amd to go beyond 16c/32t at some point (they were rumoured to have tested a 24c chip for 7000, but went with 16 possibly for thermal reasons).

author: D827 Kelly
text:
@Luminatrix FanFiction Exactly. In the Enterprise arena the Milan-X chips are monsters, and the recent Genoa Epyc chips are 96C monsters as well, with Genoa-X to follow (-X meaning they have vCache). These are the reasons they developed the vCache, as for certain enterprise level applications they make a HUGE difference, such as for a formula 1 team doing aerodynamic airflow modelling (they sponsor Mercedes, so I'd be surprised if Mercedes don't use Milan-X to their advantage) and other such specialised uses. 

Like with games, programs have to really be programmed to take advantage of the extra cache so the results can be hit or miss. With more optimisation over time, the improvements could be even better, especially if the productivity applications adapt to better use it (currently the weak point for the 5800X3D chips).

author: Luminatrix FanFiction
text: @D827 Kelly well the 5800xt3D-Vcache is capable of matching the latest current gen performance wise in some titles, so I think it'll be very interesting to see how they improve it with 7900xt3D-V

author: D827 Kelly
text: @Luminatrix FanFiction interesting point. I will be interested to see two things, 1) how much difference 3D vCache might make (we can make a guess using the difference between the equivelant 3D vCache chip and non-vCache cip in 5000 series) and 2) how much diffence might be made when paired with a AMD RDNA3 card and the infinity cache with the X670 chipsets.

author: Luminatrix FanFiction
text: Okay so my thoughts on the comparisons, AMD is slightly better in some games and only falls behind by 5 fps in other games however, what I'm seeing is AMD's cpu is running faster render ms frame rates than intel. For example, look at Halo. AMD is about 2 ms frame rates faster which is important for smooth gameplay where the game isn't looking choppy or stuttery, especially if you are using a high refresh rate monitor. So despite it being 3-5 fps marginally behind in some titles, it looks like AMD is the winner. This isn't even an 3D -cache infinity version of the cpu, so the potential is enormous.

author: Christian
text:
Unless it's some new fancy Crucial (Micron) memory, probably not a lot of difference between the two platforms. Current Micron DDR5 tends to perform at the lower end of the speed range, followed by Samsung (mid/high speeds), and finally Hynix (mid/high++).

If he equipped the systems with higher speed modules (eg. 7600+), only Intel would likely even post/function. This is one area Raptor Lake has a significant edge over Ryzen 7000 - attainable memory speeds.

author: Paul Brooks
text:
Performance alone is a fallacy. The Intel CPUs draw around 50% or more power. They are also prone to thermal throttling. If your cooling is subpar, your room is too warm (and the CPU will heat it up more), you’ll end up with less performance. Add to that the power consumption is just bad for the environment. 

If you want a quality efficient CPU, get the 8 core AMD model or lower. The lower end Intel CPUs are better in this regard, but they just don’t offer the same performance as AMD.

Last thing to note is that not all performance is equal. If you play on VR, threaded latency matters and AMD is better for that.

author: Sean Taft
text:
In Linus' situation, Intel is probably the better choice for one reason:  Thunderbolt.
Thunderbolt is an Intel property and AMD boards need a special chip to do it.  Long conversation short:  Intel is the better option because it's more likely to do what he needs for his specific use case (Thunderbolt cable from a separate room).

I know more AMD is and will be Thunderbolt 4 compliant (especiallyas USB4 and Thunderbolt 4 are close), but it's not quite there yet.

author: vix86
text:
Again when comparing the current gen CPUs, nothing was mentioned about the sockets and their longevity, _especially_ if you are building from scratch.

AMD's AM5 is likely to be around for another 3 years (maybe 5 if we get lucky). But Intel's LGA1700 for the 13th gen, is probably the *last* generation we'll see of this socket. So if you buy a 13900K -- that's it, there is no further upgrade path for your system with that motherboard. With AMD you could buy a board now and in 5-6 years when you retire the system to some other task (file server, home theater pc, or whatever), you can buy a cheap CPU and get a little more power out of the motherboard.

author: D827 Kelly
text:
This is for a very simple reason. 

Amd am5 is upto 24 pci-e lanes,  intel socket 1700 is upto 20 pci-e lanes. So you can only have 1 pci-e gen 5 m.2 unless you cut the gpu down to x8, which with gen 5 speed is probably fine with current cards and would be the same as gen 4 x16. Even x4 gen 5 would probably be fine for current gpus as that's still the equivalent of gen4 x8.

author: dracer35
text: Should have used a CPU contact frame. Makes a big difference on thermals.

author: Christian
text: @dracer35 that's pretty significant :O yeah you're right, for $5 to $15 most people could get a CF, and it's probably a cheap insurance policy given the variability in temps. Heck, that's cheaper than a tube of good thermal paste.

author: dracer35
text: @Christian That's fair. I have a sample size of 1 personally plus the information given by Gamers Nexus. For me, I saw a 12c drop on my setup. 12900ks, MSI z690 Carbon MB. Which also improved my system stability to which I am now running a -0.100 offset vcore while also overclocked 100 Mhz on the P-cores. (5.6 on 2 p-cores and 5.3 on all p-core load) Before adding the contact frame, I would get instability at stock clocks with -0.080 vcore. For me it's been the best $5 I've spent on a computer part.

author: Christian

That's kind of not true. It seems to be pretty variable. Didn't see a huge difference on my 13900K personally (few degrees). Sure, it's an improvement, but wasn't anything to write home about for me :)
That could actually be a good video to make... Comparing certain CPUs and mobos with/without CF's.
I'm almost wondering if it's related to better/worse binned CPU's (voltages)... I haven't pushed this thing to it's limits yet, so perhaps that's part of the equation.

author: Formedras
text:
For those that both don't know and don't want to look it up, that Gen-Z.2 slot on the AMD motherboard (Crosshair X670E Extreme) is for a proprietary riser card that has two M.2 slots (one PCIe 5.0, one PCIe 4.0) and has a heatsink for them positioned to be the first thing that gets air from your front fans. (Well, after your AIO radiator, anyway.)
Conversely, the Maximus Z790 Extreme (not the Hero that Linus was building on) has a DIMM.2 slot. Same purpose except that it's two PCIe 4.0 slots instead of one being 5.0, and is about the same size as a RAM slot (hence the DIMM in the name).

(I didn't know, I did look it up.)

author: FracturedButWhole
text: @Mournful3ch0 Sure, if you don't upgrade your rig that often it's not an advantage. I'm upgrading from DDR4 to DDR5 now, but I'm not going to wait 8 years for the next upgrade, and i don't think many top end builders are. Upgrading MOBO within 4 years rarely yields much performance gains. From the first high end CPU to the last on the AM4 platform on the same MOBO and DDR4, there is a 179 % increase, that's not insignificant.

author: Martin M
text:
I went with the 7700 because it was the best in stats-to-cost that was available at the time of purchace. And as it's a brand new socket type and this is basically the first generation CPU on it, any upgrades I might do down the line (and that's a big if) will likely be "significant". 

But I'm honestly of the opinion that "significant" in this case is basically saying the same that "the 1000C fire got significantly hotter, now at 1050C" it IS hotter. 50C is no joke, if your room suddenly went 50C in either direction, you'd be VERY uncomfortable until you die. Sooner rather then later. But in context of 1000C? Not that big of a difference unless it's for a very special application.
So it's more or less an inperceptible improvement or change that you'd only notice if you were actively looking for it. Turn off temperature and FPS notifications and except the handful few, people are none the wiser. As this video showed.

Dunno how long ago you recorded this but according to nvidia (see gn deep dive) the issue is not fully engaged connector rather than bending the cables.
They still covering them under warranty, but it seems its quite easy to not fully click some in and then when cable managing it can work its way looser without being very noticeable.

Might be worth an editors note.

author: Daily Corvid
text:
13700k is not great for multithreaded heavy processing (unless you can get the work done during the CPU boost period).  This is because one side of the CPU heats up too much so the whole chip has to throttle.  I think GamersNexus proved that this is caused by their LGA slot device to hold the CPU down, it doesn't distribute the pressure equally and so you get one side too much one side not enough...

Your going to then see half your thermal paste get crushed too tight and not release heat, then the other side has no pressure and doesn't touch the CPU so no heat at all draws there.  So that's why unless you spend extra on a bracket then swap out the Intel one it's gonna lead to throttling and slow you down.  You will regret going with Intel there.

Probably best off with either 12900k, it's a wee bit more price wise but you can easily get a 30% discount in most places.  For the workload your comment suggests, it's the 12900k since it's far less likely to throttle down and overheat yet it performs almost equally to the 13700k and has the same igpu so you also get your encode/decode functions.

If you aren't happy spending that much on previous generation kit, then the obvious answer is to switch to an AMD system which offers equal performance or perhaps a tiny bit more - for far less money.  Add to this the upgrade options and you're gonna spend way way less that way.

But like I said, if you are an Intel guy you will kick yourself if you don't get the 12900k instead!  But you won't know until you've had it a year.

Best of luck bro.

text:
The dream of filling out all the slots on the motherboard, AKA: the reality of PCs in the 80s and a chunk of the 90s.

author: Retro Skaff
text: I just found out how to determine APIs within games. Have separate hardware. GCN 3 is good at DirectX but bad at OpenGL,and vice versa for Nvidia's Fermi architecture. NVS 5200m (1080p) performed better on Sonic Utopia than the A12 9800e did (900p). Project 06 ran better on the AMD APU (720p) than the NVS 5200m (1024x768). I found this to be interesting as no one should make the mistake of buying the wrong gpu for the wrong API. Depending on what API your games run on you should buy your gpus that excel in those areas.

author: free88
text: ​@Casey Hallows That's just AMD sponsored influencer nonsense.  If you built a flagship level computer with a flagship level CPU, your next logical, substantial upgrade will not be the CPU.  More likely than not it will be the GPU.  The next thing or in parallel is usually better, faster, bigger internal and external storage.  So the typical fact that with AMD the socket remains the same for several years is at best irrelevant and at worst a hindrance.  From Z390 to Z790, PCI Express went from 3.0 to 5.0.  USB went from 10Gbps to 40Gbps (TB4).  Wi-fi 5 to 6E.  BT 5 to 5.3.  DDR4 to DDR5.  More and better M.2 options.  With AMD you could perhaps upgrade to the latest CPU without needing a new motherboard, say, 3-4 years later, but everything else stays stuck in the past.  I would not want an RTX 4090 on a Z390 motherboard.  Not saying it will cut its performance in half or anything like that.  But if I am buying an RTX 4090 its because I want the best possible performance out of it, and that is not going to happen on PCI-E 3.0.  BTW, between the i9-9900K (Z390) and the Ryzen 9 7950X (on the latest MB for it), you are looking at maybe 35% more CPU performance.  Not very impressive for a CPU that came out nearly 4 years later for 33% higher price (launch prices).

@dr0gaN i mean the architecture of them is the same, in other words they recognize the same instructions are able to follow them giving he same results, they output the same thing, there is no difference in what they respond when the same machine code is given as an input.

However

THE WAY they do it vastly different, meaning that despite generating he same result, their internal logic is quite different, meaning one can be faster at a specific task, say AVX2 instructions, but slower at others, or vice-versa. One is faster at multi-threading, another might be faster with latency for cache sensititive games, for example. That's called having a different microarchitecture. 


In short, same answer, different ways of thinking

author: Tyler Beaumont
text:
I mean… yeah, but they’re both designed by top of the line engineers to do the same range of tasks. If you compare it to cars for example, a Porsche 919 Evo and a McLaren Solus GT are entirely different cars designed and made by different people in different countries, and yet which is better entirely depends on the course they’re on. 

CPUs are no different. They’re all designed to run the same 3D games, offline rendering software, encoding processes and what not on the same OS, so the only real perceivable difference to performance tends to depend on which software each team was using for testing and optimisation. 

If AMD were using Maya to optimise for offline 3D rendering, but Intel were using Max or Vray, then AMD will likely run faster in Maya and Intel in Max, but beyond that, they’ll be almost identical, despite their entirely different designs.

author: Aakash Jana
text:
@ishudshutup funny fact , 5nm and 10nm aren't actual numbers. Long ago they used to mean the feature size or drain-source distance  of a transistor. With advent of FinFET these numbers are a hypothetical comparison to what if we could have transistors with such feature sizes, then how the performance would have scaled. Intel measures their process dimension different from TSMC and thus you can't quite make the old comparison hold true. 
Now about chip design. The front end HDL code for the chipsets must be highly optimised for what they are intended for but as some here mentioned they were made for similar features and so it really boils down to the compilers and simulation and verification softwares how good those are and how much the devs innovated and what decisions they made. But again you only have thus much die area and this much power target so when it comes to layout, place and route there is remarkably very little room for creativity. Last but not the least bleeding edge manufacturers do depend on 3rd parties for IP blocks/cores for certain features.

text: @Jason Chen Well then I can adjust to 90fps. My goal is balance and efficiency. I also like having performance room if I need it. So even if I had a top-of-the-line system, I wouldn't run it maxed out if I don't have to. I'll enjoy that I will have a solid system for years to come.

author: Jason Chen
text:
@poseidon3032 now you are thinking like a system engineer. The issue is that performance is overall performance at user side. At OS level, we can only predict (look ahead) so many instructions to set at the correct performance level. Hence, for gaming specifically, every single (serious) gamer would want to run at the max performance and sacrifice quality. Only some casual gamer would run perf and quality mode. Also depends on the games. 

Another thing is how human eyes work. Where we look directly, our eye's refresh rate is slow, so 30-60fps would be enough, However, human peripheral vision can be 90fps+. So the 144hz actually justifies when you are playing fps games and do make a different in terms of feel (try it).

author: poseidon3032
text: If a game can run smoothly enough at 60 with all visuals, sounds, and inputs to the max, then why not bump down the power to that level. Efficiency. Only what you need. For the higher end workloads, there's plenty of power available if needed.

author: Peter Maxwell Warasila
text:
There's a lot of stuff back and forth about whether or not the power consumption matters. I think it's plain to see that it's not a huge increase in electricity bill, so it probably doesn't matter much. However, that's not really my reason. The thermal solutions for GPUs these days are getting absolutely insane, and the CPUs look like they'll follow. I don't know what kind of generational improvements we think we're making if ultimately we're just adding more transistors, die area, and the power consumption that comes with it. Ultimately, if the performance is the same between the platforms, but one takes 20% less power for the same performance, I'm going with that one because I can spend less on cooling, power supply, and even air conditioning. Pragmatically, it probably doesn't matter, but I think efficiency is an aesthetic choice that I gravitate to. My ideal computer is also physically small, and the greatest challenge with that is always cooling these days. I don't want to have to jump up a whole case size just because I need a 3 x 120 mm radiator instead of a 2 x 120 mm. It's a preference, sure, but it's also my money so... 🤷‍♂

Also, you gotta think, 100 extra watts across an entire consumer market is nothing to scoff at. We should probably be rewarding an efficient product over just a performant product with energy being such a big deal these days, if that's something you choose to value.

author: 3polygons
text:
​@Niklas Unruh From EU, too. Most ppl in the US don't realize it can get ugly with a very severe energy crisis (am kindda old and do not remember anything like this). Electricity prices in my area are super high compared to the US ones, even while some other EU country has about 5 times my electricity cost, so, they should be able to realize it's a concern.... Yeah, AMD is definitely more frugal. Even in the higher end, where 7000s have gone more power hungry than in past AMD generations, to compete with Intel, AMD still has more efficiency per watt, in every test I've seen. Which ends up being important for specially ppl like me 3D rendering many hours (as that uses _a ton_ more energy than games) , but in this time and moment, even eu gamers, too. That said... dunno, undervolting in BIOs, or using certain apps, and even touching windows energy settings, limiting  the watts go a very long way in reducing energy costs (with both brands!) while not reducing too much performance, if done well. 

The funny aspect of it all is that most users (even freelancers in  pro work, I should now) do need way less computing than these CPUs are offering today. To the point where I can work without lags neither time out with a 13600K or a 7700X in all pro apps. Those two are IMO beyond enough for any freelancing (and gaming) activity. As much, I'd go for a 7900X or a 13700K (trying to config the bios system to use way less power than default, both systems!). Unless doing extremely intense highend work, 13900K and 7950X can be a bit of an overkill.  And I don't want to use 300W non stop many hours while rendering only in the CPU (that's around the waste with both brands in top rendering stuff, AMD a bit better. While a Ryzen 9 5950x uses a lot less power)  or rendering all day (with GPUs in rendering software happens about the same, but they 3D render  A LOT faster in GPU, so it can be quite more efficient).  If I were to use _always_ the CPU full day for 3D rendering, indeed I'd use my AM4 system (3900X, currently) with a 5950X. That one wins ALL the other CPUs (including zen 4 and Raptor Lake) in terms of efficiency, even while it's slower than the latest top end ones of both brands. 

But guess what, many pros are just using a custom made 2 cpu builds, using a pair of 5950X, or small render farms with those (due to its efficiency), to simply get even faster times than with a single 7950X. Bigger render farms I guess they'll go with cheaper cpus, as they always did.  5950X is really well designed, consumes very little power for what it achieves, and unlike other similar cpus previous to it, it has a very nice single core performance (thx to IPC, etc). Best ratio of rendered frame per watt, no matter the  (unbiased) review and benchmarks that I checked. But if you have top paying customers that require most of all speed in delivering... well, then I guess you'll just use a render farm service. Or, in some cases, build a God like machine for your own to get such crazy delivery times.  But there is a very ignorant misconception of some, that every GOOD  3D/2D pro graphic freelance artist  earns tons of money after expenses, and "should" afford a Ferrari-like PC or Mac. Nah, not to talk about myself, but I've know many amazing artists and graphic specialists, having worked at great companies, that don't go overboard with the station purchase, and aren't swimming in money, despite being top aces.

Thing is, if having already an AM4 system, if for games, I'd go for just swapping  the CPU with a 5800X3D. And for work a 5950X. Prices will settle down, cheaper mobos will appear in the future, for these two brands' new gens. It's still much cheaper than buying an entire new system and those are extremely good solutions, and about the most energy efficient (5800X3D uses less energy than even a 5800X, is pretty frugal, too). And if having an alder lake based system, you can do a good deal, too: No need to change the DDR4 RAM yet, and a 13600k / 13700k are phenomenal (I'd touch the bios and many energy settings, tho, even more so the case than with AMD).

PD: LTT typically analyzes power consumption, but here they were a bit going for "the best of the best", to make it spectacular (you know, content..)

text:
​@Corey DRIZZLE A shiny new CPU in an older motherboard has multiple times the price-to-performance ratio than going through a full platform change every single time. Also PCIE5.0 and DDR5 are here to stay for a long time, so I don't see the motherboard becoming a problem anytime soon either, as long as AMD continues their previous trend of supporting new CPUs on older motherboards with a simple BIOS update.

My concern with Intel today is LGA1700s longevity, given their socket support trends. It's almost 2023 and LGA1851 is expected to drop late-23/early-24. So in a way we have the same idea. Why would anyone upgrade to that today if it's soon to be outdated.

Of course there's no guarantee that AM5 will live as long as AM4, but I am more hopeful about them given how things have developed on the CPU market in past few years.

author: Niosus
text:
@RiceCube Tech Why are you so triggered by this? What I said is true, isn't it? They have ditched a socket before because it was more convenient to them, and they even did so twice, just recently. Sure, it wasn't on their mainstream platform, but it did happen on their high-end desktop platform.

Threadripper was high end, but certainly marketed more towards the consumer side than the business side. And this is very obvious in the branding as well. You have the regular Threadripper platform, alongside the Threadripper Pro platform (which is again another socket). Those are meant to go into workstations bought in bulk by companies.

And AMD absolutely did promise future support for sTRX4. I can't post a link here, but this is a direct quote from AMD. Feel free to Google if you don't believe me: "sTRX4 sets us up nicely for future development and scalability of the Threadripper platform, both on a near- and long-term basis."

Why AMD killed of Threadripper really doesn't matter. They made that statement by 3rd gen. They knew the market by then. I'm not even saying that they were wrong to kill consumer Threadripper (because again, Threadripper Pro is still very much alive and well). But they did make a strong statement indicating support. And they broke that promise. Which is why I'm saying: buy what's best for you now. I don't know anyone who has actually upgraded their CPU but kept their motherboard, you likely won't do it either. And even if you want to, there may be other reasons why you want/need to swap your motherboard anyway. Future-proofing is a fool's errand. Sometimes you may save some money, but often you're just spending more for a capability you'll never use.

author: Shawn Lobo
text:
@OM That had less to do with the socket itself
The problem then was the memory size of the BIOS chip or something of the sorts, and they couldn't support 1xxx to 5xxx CPUs on x370 boards. They ended up making it so that updating the BIOS would only support the latest 3xxx and 5xxx CPUs and remove 1xxx and 2xxx supports depending on the motherboards chip storage space

It's not like Intel who basically used the same socket pins (different layout) and pretty much purposely designed it to not work well with newer chips
They should've created a new socket but the heat from early Ryzen claiming support for years made it tough, so they kept the same socket and decided to call any future proof issues "for our own good"

author: Juzu Juzu
text:
@Corey DRIZZLE 12900K vs. 5950X, using 2 hours work 100% work, 2 hours for gaming, and you'll end up using 200KWh more electricity per one year. So if you upgrade once in 3 years you have used 600KWh which costs here 50% of the price of these CPUs. To get similar ratio with Lambo, even if you drive insane amounts it would have to use like 20-50 litres per one kilometer. So at that point the cost would certainly be a factor.

For some reasons techtubers talk about everything except the price of electricity, and that's stupid. The problem is that you would have to create graphs with total cost of ownership based on the amount of usage, and price of electricity. Still I would hope the biggest tech tuber to start that trend, because otherwise we get these idiotic situations like with Zen 4 where you can cut 50% of the used electricity and get 1-5% reduction of performance depending on the workload. And they kind of have to do this because people only focus on the performance and not on TCO.

author: Juzu Juzu
text:
It just shows the idiocy of these comparisons when it's purchase price that is considered and not TCO.  As with these CPUs there's really no point on going with Intel unless you either don't use your computer more than occasionally or play certain specific games competitively where Intel is faster. The cost of electricity over the course of ownership will be more than the price difference by far, if you do any work.  And if you don't do any work, you get even faster gaming with 7700X that is much much cheaper.

I really would like to see TCO calculations with these tests, perhaps that could change the course we are heading with this industry. It's insane to release CPUs with 300W power usage where you get over 80% of the performance with less than 100W.

author: Sheldon Gray
text:
@ETEcco From the Merriam Webster website 'they' definition 3b: "used with a singular antecedent to refer to an unknown or unspecified person". From the online Cambridge Dictionary 'they' definition b1: "used to refer to a person whose gender is not known or does not need to be mentioned". Lastly, from a blogpost on the Oxford English Dictionary website titled "A brief history of singular 'they'": "Singular they has become the pronoun of choice to replace he and she in cases where the gender of the antecedent - the word the pronoun refers to - is unknown, irrelevant, or nonbinary, or where gender needs to be concealed."

According to these three sources at least, using they as a singular is not wrong. "Their" gender in that sentence is unspecified because it is irrelevant and does not need to be mentioned since we have the context of the preceding sentence to know who the speaker is referring to.

author: ETEcco
text: @Desso No, using they as singular in English IS WRONG. You have to use he for gender neutral singular, they/theirs implies plurality by default, in addition transitioning from 'her' to 'their' pc without saying a proper noun that could be "they" is also wrong. You can't use a pronoun before the noun, especially if you never say the noun.

text: @Avixs quantum tunneling has absolutely nothing to do with instruction set. Silicon will need to be replaced regardless. ARM is not much more modern or better, its simply different. RISC, which is what ARM instruction set is, was developed in the 80s as well. x86 is more powerful and scales to clockspeed better, so its better for PCs and servers that need strong single threaded performance. RISC is more efficient at lower clockspeeds, so is good for mobile devices, and servers that performance/watt is the primary concern.

author: Jordan
text: @dose buss I must admit I thought this convo ended a few days ago haha. Again, I’m a optimist on technology and think we will keep breaking what we think are the limits. But, it is foolish to believe it is inevitable that we will keep advancing in the face of potential hard physical laws, as nothing about the world is for sure, and even more so that we can predict the future rate of advancement off of a relatively short trend such as semiconductor improvements for the past few decades. This discussion started on the premise that we will see similar improvements over the next few generations as what was seen say for AM4 from AMD (baring massive increases in power utilizations). I think most people who actually work in the field agree this is unlikely, at least in the era we are in (during which AM5 will exist). Perhaps in a 5, 10, 20 years we will be back to a rapid race of advancement  and decreasing costs. The one thing we can solidly take from the history of technology is that it is highly unpredictable. Things people expect to advance often doesn’t, and new areas advance beyond what people even imagined possible.

author: Jordan
text: @Gabriel Guedes Balogo lol I never said end. I have high hopes for innovating new methods that get around the limits, and even potentially restores the previously seen gains.  But as has been seen several times before, we are hitting the wall of our current fabrication methodology and getting beyond it will be tough. Further, just because people said it and were wrong before is a fallacy that it won’t be correct this time. We are working at a fundamentally different scale, with sizes nearing those of atoms, quantum tunneling effects, and frequencies that approach communication limits across CPU dies due to the limits of light speed. As AMD themselves recently stated they are no longer seeing performance gains for many parts by shrinking feature sizes, which was a primary consideration for using chiplets so they can save money on the many parts that don’t get benefits from advanced nodes. For a long time we have been facing the prospect of dark silicon, in that energy efficiency no longer increases with smaller nodes so much of the CPU needs to remain inactive (or dark) at any given time to not set it on fire. Shrinking components has allowed us to package more complex logic in the same space, allowing more feature rich hardware which can be better optimized, but it has been a long time already since we have significantly increased the amount of logic that can be used at once (this is why multi core became a bigger thing).

author: Jordan
text: @Gabriel Guedes Balogo almost all improvement in speeds come from increased cache usage, increased clock speeds, or more cores (in proper workload). The fact that zen 4 is not that different from zen 3 supports my argument. They mostly improved by doubling L2 cache and numbing clocks (which is done by increasing power, which can’t physically be done indefinitely). The point is the gen on gen gains are mostly utilizing methods that can’t be indefinitely continued (and arguably is already at a limit) and so betting on massive continuous gains in a platforms life cycle is very uncertain

To make it even better, you can most likely bundle it with the old CPU (and perhaps RAM) you are flipping to save even more time/money

author: Kadrix
text: @Dae You can get a low end CPU and in 4 years upgrade to the highest end CPU of that generation without replacing anything. Upgradability is a good thing, you can't say anything against that.

author: Jordan
text: @Crazy Beatrice it’s not really a unlikely scenario. I work in electronics fabrication and advancing that stuff is getting hard. This is why we have seen everyone push power to the limit, but that’s hitting a practical limit. Further, despite issues, full platform reworks gives greater architectural flexibility. Zen3->4 was such a rework, but we can likely expect significantly less for a more moderate zen 4->5->6. This is especially the case in the absence of power bumps. I should note core counts is one area that can increase still (at least so far), but that’s only going to effect some productivity tasks and not gaming.

author: Mavis

author: Jordan
text: You can always flip motherboards if you decide to upgrade, and intel has more room for ram upgrades in the future unlike AMD (which does give benefits, and RAM is quickly getting cheeper/faster). Further more most people don’t upgrade every 3 years, even if substantial performance gains are achieved in that time. Not saying longer platform support isn’t a nice feature, and intel should adopt at least one more year for their platforms. But in general I would always buy the better CPU for the cost at the time rather than planning for a theorized future. Until recently that was Intel, although with the price cuts on AMD it’s probably winning currently! Competition is nice

author: Jordan
text: @Unknowniti I certainly am not. A extreme example is Germany at 0.457 $/kWh. 13900k at full load is ~140 w above 7950x. So even if you are running at full bore 24/7 that’s only ~$10.74 per week. Even for gaming that not extreme (a lot of people spend much more on hobbies like a single movie/drink). And don’t forget this is a extreme example for one of the most expensive places and running at max power 100% of time. More so, I especially called out productivity in such cases of you are making money from it. $10.74 a week is surely worth it if it gives even a 1-2% increase in work throughput. Of course know your workload and don’t use a more power hungry cpu if it doesn’t give any benefit. But people have to keep these numbers in perspective. Every company is going to try to get people talking about their advantage, even if that advantage is not realistically a good metric to evaluate on for most. FYI in a place like the US and  reasonable work day of ~12 hours this equation brings it down to just $1.58 per week, and can even heat up your room if placed well and living in a cold place

text:
@Gaston Zamora To be fair the video enconding isn't as much a issue anymore for GPU choices, AMD and NVIDIA both have dual AV1 encoder/decoders and Intel QuickSync nowadasy gets a way better quality for streaming than NVENC could in any generation

The best cost-effective solution today is a Intel CPU with a AMD GPU (assuming the 7900XTX outperforms the 4080), RTX XX90 aren't even cost efficient to be considered.

HOWEVER due to how developers simple choose to give a better support to NVIDIA technology (even when consoles uses AMD GPUs) you will be missing a lot of features in some games like DLSS and DLAA, even with FSR as alternatives, some games don't even include FSR, and DLAA replaces TAA as being the best visual-performance AA solution.

As for production... it all depends of which technology do you rely on, but for gaming and streaming, either one will sufice. (as long as the CPU is Intel without a F in the name.)

author: Mr. Moʀɖɛռ
text: PCIe 5 15GB/s drives are going to have some serious problems for productivity applications that need drive writes where drives get super hot under sustained writing. The worst part is that these high end motherboard designs STILL sandwich hot m.2 drives between a searing hot GPU and the motherboard. Situated in such a way there will be little to no direct airflow, but that's not all... it will also be impossible to install better heatsinks on the m.2 drive because there is no vertical space to do it. They're going to have to work up a way to provide airflow and increase the level of cooling. Perhaps they will move drives to the back of the motherboard again and implement some sort of ducting? It's not an easy problem to solve because of the trace lengths required for stupid high speed PCIe devices.

author: SterkeYerke
text: You've got a lot more variables when comparing an APU to a dedicated graphics card though. Memory bandwidth is probably the most significant in that regard, as pretty much every APU will be memory bottlenecked since it has to fight the cpu for every bit of bandwidth there is. How much it will be bottlenecked depends on the game or application you're running, but it's not necessarily related to the API. Drivers are another variable: an APU will probably get game optimized drivers, while I'd imagine an NVS probably gets workstation optimized drivers. Different architectures can absolutely perform differently on various APIs even when the gpus are generally similar in performance, but I'd say you really have to look for a more apples to apples comparison to know for sure. Ideally you'd want them to have a very similar memory configuration as well (both having very similar bandwidth and either the same amount of vRAM, or making sure none of the games you're testing exceed the vRAM limitation of the card with less vRAM)
